<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?><TimeML><TIMEX3 tid="t0" functionInDocument="CREATION_TIME"/>A special federal assembly <EVENT eid="e1" class="ASPECTUAL" tense="PAST" aspect="NONE" polarity="POS" modality="none">began</EVENT> <EVENT eid="e2" class="OCCURRENCE" tense="PRESPART" aspect="NONE" polarity="POS" modality="none">meeting</EVENT> in Berlin  <TIMEX3 tid="t1" type="DATE">Monday</TIMEX3> to <EVENT eid="e3" class="OCCURRENCE" tense="INFINITIVE" aspect="NONE" polarity="POS" modality="none">elect</EVENT> a new German head of state to <EVENT eid="e4" class="OCCURRENCE" tense="INFINITIVE" aspect="NONE" polarity="POS" modality="none">succeed</EVENT> Richard von Weizsaecker,  who under the constitution must <EVENT eid="e5" class="OCCURRENCE" tense="NONE" aspect="NONE" polarity="POS" modality="must">retire</EVENT> after <EVENT eid="e6" class="OCCURRENCE" tense="NONE" aspect="NONE" polarity="POS" modality="must">serving</EVENT> <TIMEX3 tid="t2" type="DURATION">two five-year</TIMEX3> terms.&#13;
The winner will be the first president <EVENT eid="e7" class="OCCURRENCE" tense="PASTPART" aspect="NONE" polarity="POS" modality="none">elected</EVENT> by representatives of the  reunited Germany, and the seventh of post-war, federal Germany.&#13;
The 1,324 members of the assembly, <EVENT eid="e8" class="OCCURRENCE" tense="PRESPART" aspect="NONE" polarity="POS" modality="none">consisting</EVENT> of the 662 members of the  federal parliament and an equal number of party-nominated delegates of the 16  regional parliaments, will <EVENT eid="e9" class="OCCURRENCE" tense="FUTURE" aspect="NONE" polarity="POS" modality="none">cast</EVENT> their secret ballots in up to three rounds.&#13;
Strict security was in force around the historic Reichstag in Berlin where  the assembly was <EVENT eid="e10" class="OCCURRENCE" tense="PAST" aspect="PROGRESSIVE" polarity="POS" modality="none">taking</EVENT> place, with the building <EVENT eid="e11" class="OCCURRENCE" tense="PAST" aspect="NONE" polarity="POS" modality="none">sealed</EVENT> off by hundreds of  police to <EVENT eid="e12" class="I_ACTION" tense="INFINITIVE" aspect="NONE" polarity="POS" modality="none">guard</EVENT> against the possibility of a terrorist <EVENT eid="e13" class="OCCURRENCE" tense="NONE" aspect="NONE" polarity="POS" modality="none">attack</EVENT>.&#13;
Five candidates are in the running, with the late entry of the far-right  Republicans party, but the race is <EVENT eid="e14" class="I_STATE" tense="PRESENT" aspect="NONE" polarity="POS" modality="none">expected</EVENT> to be between the favourite Roman  Herzog and Johannes Rau.&#13;
Herzog, 60, is the candidate of the Christian Union parties <EVENT eid="e15" class="OCCURRENCE" tense="PAST" aspect="NONE" polarity="POS" modality="none">led</EVENT> by  Chancellor Helmut Kohl. He is chairman of the constitutional court. Rau, 63,  <EVENT eid="e16" class="I_STATE" tense="PRESPART" aspect="NONE" polarity="POS" modality="none">standing</EVENT> for the Social Democratc, is North Rhine-Westphalia premier.&#13;
The outcome is <EVENT eid="e17" class="I_STATE" tense="PRESENT" aspect="NONE" polarity="POS" modality="none">expected</EVENT> to be <EVENT eid="e18" class="I_ACTION" tense="PASTPART" aspect="NONE" polarity="POS" modality="none">determined</EVENT> by the minority Free Democrats,  who have their own candidate, Hildegard Ham-Bruecher, 73. Their votes could  <EVENT eid="e19" class="OCCURRENCE" tense="NONE" aspect="NONE" polarity="POS" modality="could">split</EVENT> if and when she is <EVENT eid="e20" class="OCCURRENCE" tense="PRESENT" aspect="NONE" polarity="POS" modality="none">obliged</EVENT> to <EVENT eid="e21" class="OCCURRENCE" tense="INFINITIVE" aspect="NONE" polarity="POS" modality="none">withdraw</EVENT>.&#13;
In the first two rounds of voting, an absolute majority is <EVENT eid="e22" class="OCCURRENCE" tense="PRESENT" aspect="NONE" polarity="POS" modality="none">required</EVENT>, but  on the third a simple majority will <EVENT eid="e23" class="OCCURRENCE" tense="FUTURE" aspect="NONE" polarity="POS" modality="none">suffice</EVENT>, and the Christian Union parties  have more votes at their disposal than the Social Democrats.&#13;
There is also an independent standing with the support of the Greens  party, Jens Reich, 55, but he is an outsider.&#13;
